{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_10","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Product Spec\n\nProduct: WakeTask (`com.keen.waketask`)\n\nWakeTask is a wake-accountability iPhone app focused on sustained wakefulness, not just alarm dismissal. The core model is a two-phase wake flow: mission-gated dismissal followed by post-dismiss wake verification.\n\n## Research Evidence\n\n- Users report autopilot alarm dismissal and relapse sleep within minutes.\n- Reliability trust is fragile; users keep backup alarms due to fear of missed firing or mission failure loops.\n- Competitive demand is validated for mission alarms, but incumbents are frequently criticized for ad clutter, pricing shock, and brittle flows.\n- Highest-confidence opportunities from the matrix are:\n  - post-dismiss wake assurance loop\n  - mission safety rails with fallback\n  - visible reliability telemetry and readiness checks\n  - travel-proof strictness profiles\n  - trust-first wake UX and transparent monetization\n\n## User Journeys\n\n1. Setup and first alarm\n- User grants notifications.\n- User creates an alarm and selects a mission chain.\n- App validates mission inputs at setup (especially scan targets).\n- User sees readiness state before sleep.\n\n2. Alarm firing and dismissal\n- Alarm fires at scheduled time.\n- User must complete mission chain to dismiss.\n- If mission cannot complete (invalid target/unavailable condition), app routes to accountable fallback mission.\n\n3. Post-dismiss stay-awake verification\n- After dismissal, app runs wake checks at +3, +7, and +12 minutes.\n- Missed/failed check triggers escalating re-alarm behavior.\n- Session is marked successful only when all required checks pass.\n\n4. Morning trust review\n- User opens morning reliability log.\n- User sees event timeline and fallback usage for each alarm.\n\n5. Travel context\n- User switches to a travel profile with resilient mission stack and fallback options.\n\n## MVP Scope\n\nIn scope (v1):\n- Mission-gated alarm dismissal with chain support (math, memory, motion, scan).\n- Setup-time mission validation, including scan target verification UX.\n- Accountable fallback mission path that avoids trap states.\n- Post-dismiss wake-check loop at +3/+7/+12 with escalation.\n- Per-alarm reliability log with user-visible timeline fields.\n- Context profiles: weekday, weekend, travel.\n- Trust-first wake UI: large controls, minimal decision load, non-creepy tone.\n- Transparent pricing and permissions messaging.\n\nOut of scope (v1):\n- Sleep-stage analytics platform.\n- Social/competitive wake community features.\n- Wearable-dependent wake logic.\n- Broad wellness content feed.\n\n## Boilerplate Reuse\n\nImplementation must extend `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution` and reuse platform modules. No rewrite of foundational infrastructure without explicit ADR approval.\n\nMust reuse:\n- `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`\n- `Config/App.xcconfig`\n- `Packages/Core`\n- `Packages/Networking`\n- `Packages/Storage`\n- `Packages/Auth`\n- `Packages/Payments`\n- `Packages/AI`\n- `Packages/FeatureSettings`\n- `Packages/Localization`\n- `Packages/DesignSystem`\n- `CompositionRoot`\n\n## Design Direction\n\n- Principle: “3:30am-safe UX”.\n- Alarm-critical screens prioritize large targets, low cognitive load, and high-contrast clarity.\n- Progressive friction model: light cognitive -> moderate cognitive -> physical validation.\n- Tone policy: neutral/strict coach options; no manipulative or intimate notification language.\n- Wake-critical paths avoid ad-like clutter and accidental-tap traps.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. Mission completion rules\n- `math`: user completes configured number of problems; each answer validated before advance.\n- `memory`: user reproduces sequence with exact-match threshold.\n- `motion`: user achieves configured motion signal threshold.\n- `scan`: user scans validated target; if unavailable, fallback mission is required.\n\n2. Post-dismiss schedule and outcome\n- Wake checks trigger at +3, +7, +12 minutes after dismissal timestamp.\n- Any missed/failed check triggers escalation re-alarm.\n- Session success requires all scheduled checks to pass.\n\n3. Fallback safety protocol\n- If primary mission input is invalid/unavailable, app must present fallback mission within one user step.\n- Fallback route cannot dead-end or trap user in unrecoverable loop.\n- Fallback usage is logged in reliability telemetry.\n\n4. Reliability telemetry fields (per alarm)\n- Required: `alarm_scheduled_at`, `alarm_fired_at`, `dismissed_at`, `wake_check_results`, `fallback_used`, `profile_used`.\n- Morning log renders these fields in a user-readable timeline.\n\n5. Permissions behavior\n- Notifications requested before first active alarm enablement.\n- Camera requested only when scan mission is configured.\n- If camera denied, user gets non-camera fallback mission option and clear recovery path.\n\n6. Trust and policy constraints\n- No credential values or environment variable dumps in logs/reports.\n- Secret checks may emit boolean presence only.\n- No guaranteed-wake claims in UI/metadata; language must reflect iOS platform limits.\n\n7. Quality gates\n- Blocking checks: `xcodebuild build`, `xcodebuild test`, SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scanning, App Store string audit.\n\n## Appium Exploratory QA\n\nRequired exploratory run outcome file: `reports/ios/appium-exploratory-report.json`\n\nPass contract:\n- Real simulator/Appium run executed unless workflow input explicitly sets `defer_appium: true` and documented blocker exists.\n- Explorer taps every reachable enabled control in MVP flows with bounded-depth traversal.\n- Report includes:\n  - `ok` (boolean)\n  - `buttons_tapped` (integer)\n  - `screens_visited` (integer)\n  - `crashes` (integer)\n  - `failures` (integer)\n  - `failures_detail` (array)\n- Pass threshold:\n  - `ok=true`\n  - `crashes=0`\n  - `failures=0`\n  - `buttons_tapped >= 25`\n  - `screens_visited >= 8`\n\n## App Store Readiness\n\n- 4.3 differentiation narrative must be explicit: two-phase wake model + reliability log + mission safety rails.\n- Metadata and in-app strings must avoid clone-like generic claims and avoid “guaranteed wake” wording.\n- Privacy disclosure must match actual permission usage and explain camera/notification purpose clearly.\n- Release hardening requires string/metadata audit pass before TestFlight handoff.\n\n## Definition of Done\n\nSee `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`. All checklist items are blocking unless explicitly marked deferred with owner and date.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
